body:
@psuter in your last example i'ld argue that those parameters are not forwarded as they are explicitly bound to a function (a bit like currying the function even?). These edge-cases make things more complicated though, as they break with our assumption of JSON-in, JSON-out as those parameters would need to be handled in a special way, even though they are part of the object given to the function in the first place.

In general, do we define the sequence itself as a composition of functions: 

```
f2(f1(args));
```

or more like a wrapper around a composition of functions:

```
sequence(args) {
    f2(f1(args));
}
```

In case of a wrapper function it feels way more natural, that every function has access to the arguments given to that wrapper function, while not having access bound to the actions explicitly as in @psuter s last example.

As others have noted, this comes down to whether we want to make things **easy** or **safe**? I lean towards the latter.

One point I'd like to re-emphasize is that action sequences aren't the only way to compose actions. You can always write an action that invokes other actions with the exact parameter passing semantics you want.

Here's an example (in pseudocode) that neither alternative A nor B address:

```
output1 = action1(input);
output2 = action2(output1 + input} // merge input parameters
output3 = action3(output1 + input.foo} // merge output1 (not output2!) and some input parameters
return output3
```

In JavaScript (with promises and some helper functions) it might look like this:

```
function main(input) {
    var p1 = whisk.invoke('action1', input);

    var p2 = p1.then(function(output1) {
        return whisk.invoke('action2', merge(output1, input));
    });

    var p3 = p2.then(function(output2) {
        return whisk.invoke('action3', merge(output1, {foo: input.foo}));
    });

    return p3;
}
```

(I'm sure we can come up with a cleaner and more concise syntax than the above, but I wanted to show it's possible without a lot of code.)

For reference, here's how piping semantics (alternative A) would look like as code:

```
function main(input) {
    var p1 = whisk.invoke('action1', input);
    var p2 = p1.then(function(output1) { return whisk.invoke('action2', output1) });
    var p3 = p2.then(function(output2) { return whisk.invoke('action3', output2) });
    return p3;
}
```

And here's alternative B as code:

```
function main(input) {
    var p1 = whisk.invoke('action1', input);
    var p2 = p1.then(function(output1) { return whisk.invoke('action2', merge(input, output1)) });
    var p3 = p2.then(function(output2) { return whisk.invoke('action3', merge(input, output2)) });
    return p3;
}
```

Developers don't mind writing code, so let them code.
